And with that, the boys went to the garage, fired up their dirtbikes, put on their goggles and rode them to the curb before taking a hard right,
Taking Billy’s road south lead to the kings highway, which split Catuvella downtown from its boonies and heartland, and ran from Orc Harbor to Seaside road. But the boys headed north, a few blocks to the right of the Wolcotts house, where the street came to an end at a cul-ve-sac, crowned by a dirt path walled by lobster traps stacked ten feet high. This path, dubbed the Root, bypassed some conservation forest and ran parallel to the old Catuvella cemetery before dumping the two boys down a steep but short cliff into the abandoned east-west railroad. 
Beside the browned and rusted steel tracks the boys flew. Billy up front in his yellow model, Roger tailing close in red, as close as he could without eating a mouth full of frosted debris and gravel. With 250cc the boys reached their destination rather quick, spotting the c-shaped ramp and revving down before entering it. The transition from dry dirt and gravel to sand and crushed leaves was smooth, and once they were over the hump and in Honeymoon forest they walked the last half mile before the pond. 
The heat of the engine and the excitement of riding distracted Billy from, among other things, how cold it was. He only realized the temperature when he wasn’t moving fast enough to see his breath fog in front of him. 
“Its cold.” He said aloud, enjoying the frigid air against his still-burning ears. “The ice will be thick when we get there.”
“Sweet.” Roger replied, lagging behind as he struggled to push the large machine. “Did you bring skates?”
“No.”
Crunching leaves and twigs underfoot, Billy enjoyed the serenity of the forest. His nerves calmed as the smell of rotting leaves and wet bark hit his nose. As the clearing where Deadman’s pond lay came into view, the aroma changed. Now the crisp smell of naturally frozen fresh water hit the boys nostrils, invoking visions of past hokey games at black pond. Finally reaching the sand-floored landing of the pond, they propped their bikes on kickstands, and walked on the ice. 
“This is nice.” Billy said, staring at the ice beneath his feet.
“I know!” Roger took his goggles off and shoved them in his pocket. “Fuck man, I wish we brought our skates. Its like perfect over here by the beach.”
“Yeah.” Billy’s thoughts shifted from the ice a to what lay beneath it. Not here where he stood but... somewhere else at that pond. “Lets keep walking.”
“Okay. We gonna measure the dimensions of the good stuff?” Roger pondered what sort of benefit he could make out from this trip. “Maybe we can come here in the weekends.”
“Yeah.” The blond boy was no longer thinking about hockey. “Maybe.”
