But Roger was okay with that. 
He denied that it was one sided, but he had made a silent agreement to be Billy’s guide. So when Billy was not thinking about what was important, such as the intricacies of ice texture that affected how much resistance a puck had to a stick, Roger would be there to guide him.
So Roger put his hand on Billy’s shoulder, ready to say they should stop their fourth time walking the ice, When he heard something southwards.
Or Rather, someone.
By their bikes on the shore was a blood crimson truck that looked as old as sin. And standing behind its opened door was none other than the cream-furred rabbit Elizabeth Dagger. 
“Ah fuck.” Roger said, and he started towards the shore.
“Villiam Volcott, yu ar in trouble!” 
“Fuck off lady he’s busy!” Came Roger, trudging against the ice in earnest defense of his friend’s deep thought.
