Roger sighed a cloud of defeat while Elizabeth started for her truck.
Then, taking a step towards the shoreline, Billy heard a crack, and splashed through the ice without so much as a scream.
Instead Roger was the one to scream, falling to his knees and shaking.  “Oh fuck oh fuck oh fuck.” He grabbed his face, wringing and messaging his cheeks with his fingers as thoughts of having lost his friend filled his mind. He pounded the sand where he knelt and cried.
Elizabeth saw Billy was gone over her shoulder, and started to run away from the shore.  
Beneath the ice Billy struggled, swimming against the roof hoping to bump into the hole he blundered into. But light was a cruel bitch underwater, and what seemed to be an exit was just another wall in that muddy darkness. He felt goosebumps all over his body as his clothes absorbed the lake. His throat aching for a breath of fresh of air. His fingers, cut and bruised from yesterdays box shenanigans, further ached as he pressed and shoved against the ice. As seconds past his cheeks felt like they were going to burst and his lungs screamed and all he could do as he sunk to the bottom was think an endless tide of terror and despair. 
Meanwhile, back on the shoreline, Elizabeth tied a rope from the hitch of her truck to herself. She mounted the closest dirtbike, Roger’s own red beast, and revved it to life. Positioning it before a soil-topped stump along the shore, she throttled forward and ramped off the stump to smash through the ice.
Exploding into the cold waters, the rabbit lady let the bike sink to the bottom and searched for the boy. She spotted him at the bottom, back flat against the mud, and ignoring all ideas that she was too late, grabbed him and hoisted him skywards. 
Roger watched as through the massive hole in the ice she created, Elizabeth emerged, Billy over her shoulder. 
She sluggishly brought herself onto the ice, walked back to shore, and then threw billy on the comparatively warmer sand. She ripped open the puffed flannel of his jacket and groped her paw-beans agaisnt his chest, pressing once, twice, three times before bring her lips to his and repeating the process. Finally, Billy coughed, and puked fresh water. 
“Oh mein gott...” She slapped a fist against his stomach, making him cough again. “Dont yu scare me like sat hever hagain.” 
Though he smiled, Billy didn’t care to say a word. Instead, he brought his clutched fist up to the rabbits face, brushing his knuckle against her furred-cheek, and then opened his hand to show her a small bronze ring inscribed with initials 'J.C.'

Chapter 6

Billy made a request after being resuscitated. “Pppp please don’t take me to my dad.”
And so they, freezing wet rabbit, freezing wet sophomore and dry freshman, chucked the one remaining dirt bike into the back of the sixty year old truck and piled into its cabin. Before diving a dirtbike into the frozen pond, Elizabeth had enough sense to turn the archaic vehicle’s heat on. And so the drive to reknowned furniture, while humid,  was at at least warm.
And quiet, except for the buzz of the ventilation. Roger offered a few comments on how his bike was treated but shut up once they were underway. 
Billy didn’t remember what the drive was like, other than bump-filled and so fast that it was possible they had violated the speed limit once or twice if not constantly. But they only stopped when they reached the back of renowned furniture. How he got into the bathtub was a blur. 
He spent at least an hour in it. To his side was Elizabeth, administering hot water into the tub in increments so as to slowly raise his temperature. Pressing against his forehead every now and then with her padded fingers. Making him feel pampered, fragile and in need of constant attendance, like a baby. And so when he was fully aware of this, he said “Aren’t you going to need a bath too?”
“Schiesse, I vas not in for as long as yu vere.” She tugged at the tuft of her on her chest. “Und I have fur.”
Then he noticed that she was in a new set of dry clothes, a blue skirt and a wifebeater. Without a bra, if he was correct in his judgment of those bumps along her chest.
And then he realized he was in no clothes beneath the water. 
With a splash he brought his legs to his chest and said “I think I’m fine now!”
The rabbit girl at first raised an eyebrow, muzzle dipping for a scowl. And then she stopped, and realized he wasn’t showing a lack of gratitude. 
And so she laughed, laughing as she stood up to head for the bathroom door. “Yur friend said he vas getting yu closses. I vil be right out ze door for yur privacy.”
“Thanks.” 
Billy puffed out his crimson cheeks and sighed. “Fuck me, why am I embarrassed?” he thought. “Wasn’t my end goal something like this? Now she’ll think of me like a kid. Or gay. Fuck.”
He raised his arm out of the tub and rubbed its porcelain exterior. Maybe she already thought of him like a kid. Undressing him and throwing him in the bath, feeling his forehead and all. All actions Billy felt were mother-like, on top of being kind and caring. 
Kind and caring. 
Past the door Billy could hear the sound of a microwave. Sounded just like the model at his house. 
She could’ve taken him home, he thought. Expose the chittering mess to his father and then once again he would feel the clap of the belt. 
But she didnt. She took him to her house, thawed him in her own private bathroom, and even gave him privacy when he asked. On top of rescuing him from certain death beneath the ice. 
As Bill looked around the bathroom, he felt a warmth in his heart. 
“I think I love her.” He whispered.
“So vat vere yu doing at sat pond?” Elizabeth yelled from the other room.
“What were you doing there?”
“I vas ze one asking se questions.” He heard the creaking of floorboards outside as she stepped closer to the bathroom. “I called yur house und talked to your faser und he said yu vere at sat pond.”
Billy slapped his forehead. Of course he wasn’t going to get off scot-free. He sighed before asking “How did you know where I was? Did my dad give you directions?”
It was her turn to sigh, barely audible with the distance between them. “It vas vere my foster faser died.”
“Mr Dovin-Basil?”
“Ja.”
Silence fell on the apartment, save for the drip of water from the bathroom faucet. 
“Hello?” Elizabeth broke the silence. “Ar yu svalloing vater?”
“Oh no I’m fine!” He splashed until some water smattered the tiled walls. 
“Stop splashing or I vill throw you back in the pond!” She hollered, making him chuckle. When his laughter died down, he had one more question.
“So this store specializes in selling your dad’s stuff?”
“Foster faser, ja.” 
“Cool.”
Silence again. Billy wondered how long until Roger would get back with some dry clothes. Maybe his wet clothes were drier now. He could wear them home, sneak past dad, get in pajamas before being noticed. Get warm under the covers and dream of a different opportunity to be naked in a bath with Elizabeth.
He fantasized different occasions with the lapine lass. And as the idea of marriage came up he kept thinking about proposing with a ring. A ring. The ring.
The ring that he found at the bottom of the pond. 
“Hey Lizzy.” He called, having come up with the nickname for her while daydreaming. “Do you have that ring?”
There was a clattering of paws against wood and what sounded like heavy boards. “Ja. Is in yur pocket vere I put it. But not for you to keep.”
Before he could ask what she meant by that, Billy heard Roger yelling at the top of his lungs.“Captain Wolcott, your relief has arrived.” 
The metal stairs clanged and the wooden floorboards creaked and then to the bathroom doorway came Roger. Onto the pink-tiled floor by the tub he tossed a couple pairs of paints and dress shirts. “Get dressed so we can escape this wenches’ clutches.” 
“Thanks Raj. Dad suspect anything?”
“Nah my dad wasn’t at home.” Roger said, sill standing in the doorway with his back to Billy. “And luckily neither were my brothers. Those clothes too tight?”
“I was talking about my dad. But no, they fit fine.” The blonde said, toweling off his head while in new garbs. “Get me my belt, will ya?”
“Sure.” The freshman walked away from billy’s view, yelling “Speaking of belts, I think we don’t have to worry about replacing yellow’s.” 
“Vil you turn yur voice down?” Spat the rabbit woman, standing in Roger’s face. He half expected her to smack him and raised his arms in defence. Only to feel the leather belt be placed in his hands.
“What happened to yellow?” 
As he listened to Roger relay the story of the dirtbikes fate in saving his life, Billy kept watch of Elizabeth. Sitting on the bed apst the spiral staircase, she was busy looking at something with a magnifying glass. Though she showed a lack of interest her apathetic frown became a slight smile. Perhaps of embarrassment, or out of pride, Billy couldn't tell. But it was a smile that he would like to see until the end of his days.
"But don't worry!" The freshman capped off his tale. "We still have red! Well still keep it at your house, and I'll ask for a new one my birthday. That cool?"
"Yeah." Not a single word had actually been understood by the sophomore. And Roger knew it by how little his friend spoke. So taking Billy’s shoulder, he pointed at the stairs and said “Its getting late, we should go.”
“Vait.” Dropping the magnifying glass into the pink covers, Elizabeth raised from her bed. “I vill give yu a ride home.” 
The boys didn’t turn down the offer. It was dark outside, and the old lights of the truck barely illuminated the road as they drove. Their first destination, Roger’s house, was at the east side of town along the bay, no more than a two minute drive.
 Light reflected off the shiny-black shutters as they pulled into the driveway. It was L-shaped, a white-washed whaling captain’s lodge. Bolted to its western face, a steel nameplate, with golden letters that read “Jebediah’s Redoubt.” 
Before Roger left the truck, Elizabeth made a quick announcement.
“Tomorrow, I vill need both of yu und any friends yu have for a serious task.” Her attention shifted from Roger to Billy. “Yu do sis, I vill consider it repayment for saving yur life und I vill forgive ze destruction of my property.”
“Deal!” Billy didn’t didn’t even wait to talk to Roger. He wanted nothing more than to get on the rabbit’s good graces. 
“Good.” 
Roger opened the door, waving goodbye to his friend and walking inside as slow as possible. Most polite people would have waited in the driveway for their guest to reach the door before leaving. Elizabeth reversed as soon as Roger was out of the truck, and headed for Billy’s house. Leaving the runt of the reverend to watch as his friend drove off with a strange rabbit. 
Said friend was absolutely enamored with the lapine. Leaning against the passenger window, he casually glanced and peaked at her before shifting focus to the road. His attention wasn’t on the physical beauty of her. Though there was plenty before him. How the shirt curved around her chest to confirm that she did indeed have a row of eight nipples. How the saphire skirt tightened against her thighs as she hit the gas. Little details he did note at the back of his head but weren’t what he deliberately thought.  Rather, he just imagined being the one to drive her next time, to be her personal chaffeur. 
When she looked right ways coming onto the rotary, Elizabeth noticed his stare. “Yu okay?”
“Oh yeah I’m fine.” Billy straightened his back against the leather seat. “I uh, ow you a lot, Lizzy.”
“Elizabeth.” She retorted.
“Elizabeth.” He said respectfully, heart fluttering as he thought about saying ‘I am forever grateful to you’ only to hold back. ‘Saying something like that isn’t cool.’ He chided himself. ‘I’m going to be cool. I’m going to be cool and that’s how she’ll love me.’
A right turn and a couple blocks of houses past and they reached Billy’s house. Dad was standing in the doorway, nursing a beer.
Taking a deep breath, He sauntered up to the truck, and opened the passenger-side door. “Go to bed.” Billy obeyed, first running a few steps, then stopping to wave at Elizabeth. With a weak but warm smile, Elizabeth waved back, and said “See yu tomorrow.” 
Then she addressed the boy’s father. “Thank yu for yur help. Ven he verks vith me tomorrow, he will have paid his dets.”
“Good.” Mr Wolcott closed the truck door and returned to his home, leaving her in silence. 
The silence carried on into her drive as she took the wrong turn at the rotary. A left here, a right there, casually getting lost down roads whose name she didn’t bother to read. It was all foreign to her, worth nothing more than resentment so long as she was stuck there. Forever unable to greet them again. Or give a proper goodbye. Or feel their warmth in a group hug. Or even see them, for even in the most intimate and important memories, their faces were nothing more than a cloud fading into nothingness. And until she saw them again would she never feel peace. 
Somehow in getting lost in her thoughts Elizabeth found her way back to the parking lot behind reknowned furniture. She walked around to the front entrance, the back door now boarded up. Once she was before her bed again, the rabbit woman collapsed onto the covers and sighed. 
Grabbing the magnifying glass and returning to her deep focus, Elizabeth thought about Billy. That despite all the trouble he caused, the boy could be a boon.
Turning over the bronze ring in her paws, Elizabeth whispered “Jetzt hast du deinen frienden."

By 10pm, Catuvella was asleep, her myriad of roads and passages tucked under darkness save for the black-steel streetlamps along main street and the more modern lights parallel to the king’s highway.
To drive at night down Seaside road, after going on the aforementioned streets, you would find no light. From its bustling residential zone, where every square inch was packed with cottage, mansion, resort or parking lot, to the mostly untouched conservation of Webb’s causeway. The town slept.
Though some parts more than others, such as on Webb’s island. Where the weather dome stood over the treetops, her interior abandoned though exterior not forgotten by everyone. At day it was a landmark, the last man-made building seen by every fishing ship and clamming skiff before they exited Orc harbor. At night, it was the preferred hiding spot for Catuvella P.D.’s own Officer Williams. 
In his cruiser he slept much like how he did winter nights before. Bundled in blankets, with the heater blasting and the seat reclined. This was his self-imposed vacation, a gift for working so hard in the summer dealing with drunk teens and lost foreigners during the AM. An easy shift where nothing disturbed him.
And then he heard it. 
Thunk. 
Thunk.
Officer Williams opened his eyes and brushed aside crumbs. He didn’t see anything out of his windshield. 
Thunk.
Thunk. 
He turned the keys on his car, and then blasted his brights. Every tree in the forest ahead of him was illuminated. 
But he didn’t see anyone.
Thunk.
Thunk.
The policeman took a deep breath and reached for his radio. “Dispatch, Dispatch this is Officer Williams.”
“Williams, this is dispatch, come back.” The radio cracked.
“Yeah I took a detour to Webbs for a leak, and heard a strange noise.” He said, eyeing the building to the right of his car. “Possible trespassers in the abandoned weather station. Going to kick them out, over.” 
“Roger that. Dispatch standing by.” 
And so Williams threw off his blankets, opened his car door and started for the dome. He didn’t feel it necessary to lock the car. What idiot kid tresspasser would be willing to commit a felony?
Thunk. Thunk.
Again came that noise, this time in rapid succession. Just when he was standing before the weather station’s entrance. Williams reached for his pistol, a Colt m1911 with a flashlight attachment. Turning on the flashlight, he also maintained the safety as he stepped through the rotting passage. 
 His nasal cavities filled with snot as they adjusted to the musky interior. Thought it was dark the flashlight revealed that nothing much was really inside. There was grass growing through the moss-covered hardwood floor. A rusted white desk was turned on its side beneath the stairway leading to the dome. A wooden beam, nibbled on by termites he could probably see if he stepped closer, hung down the middle of the ceiling. 
Thunk. Thunk.
Williams pointed his gun skyward. The noise was coming from the next floor up. He was sure that it was just a kid or two messing with him though. “Hello? This is the police.” He sidestepped closer to the stairs as he yelled. “You’re trespassing on condemned property. Don’t make me come up there.” 
Truth be told he didn’t want to go up there. The wood of the stirs was rotting and in some places gonee, just the metal under frame remaining. 
Then the noise came again.
Thunk Thunk Thunk. 
And this time he felt like that was an acknowledgment of him, teasing him, even intimidation. Whoever was up there was challenging the officer. 
So Williams climbed the stairs. Slowly, taking each step bit by bit, keeping his pistol trained upwards. He didn’t dare turn off the safety. A negligible discharge at best towards a kid? Or worse, a harmless animal? 
Nothing was in front of the stairs at the top. Noone was peering over the side. There wasn’t even a telescope or whatever he thought went in a dome like this. 
So, three steps from the top and seeing naught but the bolts and beams making the weather dome, Officer Williams breathed a sigh of relief. “Must’ve been the wind or... or a woodpecker.” 
He started down the stairs, and then he heard it.
Thunk.
And then the stair beneath his foot gave way.
He slipped downwards, through the board, rght before his stomach caught in the wood.
“FUCK.” He yelled, his pistol dropping. In the dark he struggled, heaving and kicking without any vision as the flashlight pointed at the door.
Then, the steps in front and ahead of him between which he was stuck, also broke. 
He landed on his ass, smacking against the desk, which surprisingly maintained his weight though groaning.
“For fucks sake.” Williams cursed , stepping off the abandoned furniture and rubbing his ass. 
Thunk thunk.
He picked up  his pistol and made a quick egress out of the building, before stopping to catch his breath.
“All that for nothing but ass pains.” The officer said, tapping the side of his pistol flashlight. It flickered, and then died. “And a broken flashlight.”
The pistol was holstered, a deep breath was taken, and the cop walked back to his car. 
Thunk.
Thunk.
THUNK. 
It was right behind him. Williams spun on his heel, hands on his pistol, only to freeze.
Standing before him, reeking of sea water and dead fish, the long overcoat of a naval captain of yore. Seaweed hung from a mud-drenched tricorn, reaching past its shoulders in a cruel aquatic imitation of human hair. And under that hat, amongst the briny tangle of red weed, the head of a feline, fur and skin missing from its muzzle to reveal ghost white bone and teeth.
“Hello laddie.” Its words, her words for the voice was distinctly female albeit husky, seemed to ooze out. Like the last gurgles of a drowning victim. “Don’t be afraid.” 
She walked right up to the human’s face, still frozen in fear. She raised her right hand up to caress his cheek, and he realized it wasn’t claws scratching him. For what reflected the light of his cop car was nothing more than the corroded remains of a three pronged clamming rake, crudely attached to her hand as a make shift prosthetic.
“Why don’t we go for a swim?”
Minutes later, against the hum of the engine and the sounds of a man being dragged through the woods, the cruiser radio barked “Williams, Williams, this is dispatch. Come back, over.”
“Williams, Williams, this is Dispatch. Come back, over.”
“Williams?”

Chapter 7 

“Yeah, I didn’t sleep at all last night.” Yawned Roger. His exhale became a swirling cloud that evaporated as he walked through. “It was like, every cop car in town was driving by my house last night.” 
“Was it the rabbit lady?” Frank eyed the furniture store, worry plastered across his face. “Did she rat us out?”
The signal to cross lit up, and Billy shoved his two friends forward into the street. “No. Come on, we can’t be late.” 
Frank stopped in the middle of the road and looked over his shoulder. Behind him was nothing but a wall of fog and the sidewalk he left. “Is she blackmailing you? Is that why you’re in a hurry to get to her?”
“No, I’m repaying her.” Billy grunted, waving his friend on. “...with your help.” 
“So she is blackmailing us.” The tall boy pulled at his dreadlocks, chuckling with guilt. “She’s hopping mad!”
 A truck honked as the frost-glazed crossing light started to flicker. The highschoolers hastily traversed the king’s highway, and then main street onto the sidewalk that lead to their destination. Far to the east, the Episcopal church wasn’t visible, blocked by fog. 
 “I think Frank’s got a point.” Roger rubbed his baggy right eye. “By holding our team captain hostage, we have no choice but to help.”
“I’m not a hostage.”  The blonde whirled to glare at his friends, his gold-haired unibrow scrunched in a scold. Roger and Frank stepped back, the shortest of the two mumbling “Fuck, why so angry?” 
The team captain stopped and took a deep breath and rubbed his head. “...I just want to clear my name, alright?”
“Alright man, glad you’re being transparent.” Frank punned, though noone chuckled. Instead Roger talked.
“What if we don’t like what she asks?” 
“I wont make you guys do it, then.” Billy replied.   
“What if that’s her plan?” The tall boy eyed a starling as it perched on an overhung gutter. “Give us impossible tasks, and then she’ll keep you forever? You know what that is?”
His two friends paused to look at him.
“A hare-brained scheme.”
Then he received a fusillade of punches to the shoulder among some laughs.  Wiping a tear from his eye, Roger looked across the street. “Where’s Mikey?” 
“I don’t know, man.” Bill said, opening the rime-coated door to renowned furniture. “He said his parents would be home tonight, so he should be here.”
Once everyone was within the dark building, Billy continued. “Even if he’s a no show, we’ll be fine. We’ll be able to do the job.”
To his friends, this was the first time they had seen the dark interiors of the store. In the short time since it was last dusted new cobwebs seemed to have popped up in every corner and a fresh blanket of grime had settled on every surface. Worse, at least in Franks eye’s since it made him want to leave, the room wasn’t lit by any of the studio lights overhead. 
Bright, flickering light was pouring out from the third floor. It reflected off the bronze locks and steel handles and flax-lined novels walled on the bookcases. Giving the intramural a smoggy, orange hue. 
“Elizabeth?” Called Billy as the three boys walked between the walls of knicknacks. There was no response. 
A book caught Roger’s eye, a turquoise whale imprinted on its side. He stepped aside and pulled it out, the cover reading “The history of -”, its topic scratched out from the leather binding long ago. Flickering through the pages revealed shoal maps off the coast of Catuvella, underwater topography, and diagrams of lighthouses, light ships and bouys.
At the foot of the spiral staircase Billy called again. “Elizabeth?”
Frank looked over Roger’s shoulder. “Is that a nipple?”
“Label says deck prism.” 
“Guys, fuck off.” Interjected Billy. “She wouldn’t want you-”
“Scheisse, boy, vy so hangry?” 
From the top of the staircase descended Elizabeth, candle in hand. Garbed in a loose grey dress which slid down the steps like flowing water, she walked slowly. Bill felt his heart burn as he stared at her, fantasizing how well she’d look in a wedding dress.
“Sorry.” spoke the lapine lass. “Ze door repairman came und sey vanted electric locks und sey popped a fuse und now I have to use candles.
While his blonde friend was busy with an open mouth, Roger spoke with indignation. “Hey lady, what’s with the dress?”
“It came with ze candles.” She passed Billy and asked “Are sey avare vere sey are?”
“Huh?” was all the boy could say, tripped up by her wording and accent. 
Brushing him aside, she swayed her hips as she walked towards Roger. The short boy was dumbstruck, not by her beauty but how strange she looked up close in the dark. 
“Sis...” She snatched the book out of his hands and closed it. “is mein foster faser’s, Mister Dovin-Basil.”
Frank peaked up, whispering. “Wait, wasn’t that...” He took an elbow to the ribs from Roger, who coughed a “yes.” 
The rabbit lady continued, walking back to the leader of the pack. “Mein Foster Faser collected hartifacts from as long ago as Vebb’s village.” 
Then she held up her hand-paw, showing off the bronze ring labeled “J.C.” on her finger. “Sis vas ze last sing he showed me before his deas, und I sink it vas himportant enough to him he vore it to his deas.” 
Carefully, sliding the ring up her digit and past the little pink paw pad tip, Elizabeth held it up to the light. “Hold out yur hand.” 
Billy did so, and clasping the circlet in his caloused palm, the rabbit gave her mission. 
 “I vant yu to rebury sis ring vith mein foster foser.”
He ever carefully put the ring in his breast pocket as The lapine lass turned and started up the stairs. “I vill change now.”
The ring in a protected spot, Billy scratched his chin. “You know what, maybe we are going to need Mikey.”
“I’m not doing it.” Declared Roger. “This goes against my beliefs.”
“Oh come on Raj!” The blonde was angry again. “We have the dead’s relatives permission.” 
“It’s sacrilege to desecrate body after it’s been buried!” The short boy looked around the store, nervous. “Also, you said if we didn’t want to do it, you wouldn’t make us.”
“Yes. We, as in You,the team that aren’t the captain.” He pointed at both his friends. “You have to decide democratically.” 
“We didn’t agree to that.” The freshman spoke a high pitched voice, meaning to sound distraught but coming off like a whine.
“Well that’s how we dealt with similar shit.” Billy was in Roger’s face. 
“Well I say no.” Roger straighted his back and grit his teeth before looking at the third of the group. “Frank?”
“Uhhhhhh.” It was his turn to look around the room and shake his knees. “I don’t really dig grave robbing, buuut...”
“HAH!” spat Roger to his team captain, making the blond clench his fist. 
“But I don’t want to not to do it, otherwise we get snitched on.”
In the floor above ,Elizabeth hummed a tune as she folded the dress. She enjoyed listening to the drama below, chuckling as she purred “Ihn’n zum spott und zum verdross...” 
“Oh so you’re just gonna play the middle?” 
“Back off Roger, its his right.” 
The two friends were squaring off, fists clenched at their sides though noone raised or shouted. Frank stepped between them, arms raised, and said “Why don’t we just let Mike be the tie breaker.” 
“Deal” was said simultaneously, and then the boys took deep breaths and watched the door. 
The avoidance of a fight was appreciated by Billy. The vice had started to tighten around his brain, and he didn’t want to risk losing his cool in front of a girl.
 The girl. 
Elizabeth was more than just some girl to him at this rate. And he wouldn’t let himself be dragged down, especially not by one of his insubordinates.
Insubordinates. He repeated the word in his head, wondering “Why..?”
Then Mikey walked through the door, and Billy’s brow was furled again. “shit.”
“Sorry!” Chided Mikey as he held the glass door open. In ran four little gingers, the eldest not even six years old. Agnes was her name, and she grabbed Frank’s dreadlocks until he screeched. While five year old Aileen kicked the tall boy’s shin until he fell over. Aran, who wasn’t yet four ran after Roger, begging for piggy back rides. While three year old Angel laughed, watching Roger hop a top the store desk to escape the little menace. Then Angel saw Billy’s frown, and started to cry. 
“Agnes! Get off mikey! Aileen, I will spank you!” Mike started for the two nuisances, then reversed to pick up the sister that was crying. “My parents had to drive to fucking Bristol for a union meeting last minute.” 
The blonde boy put his hands in his pocket and raspberried to let off steam, causing Angel to chuckle.
“Its alright Mike. You down to go grave robbing?”
“Fuck yeah,  so long as it keeps them busy.” 
“Thats unfair!” Yelled Roger, Aran jumping in front of him with arms raised. “Your violating my first amendment! This is tyranny of the majority!” 
His statements weren’t addressed as Billy lifted up Aileen by the arms. “Hey you little thing!” He said in a cheery tone. “Do you want to learn how to use a shovel?”
She answered by kicking him in the spleen. 
“All-lee!” Yelled the redheaded boy, his voice coming out hoarse. 
A weird noise came out of Billy’s throat, and he dropped the girl. She landed on her feet and returned to kicking Frank. Mike exchanged the crying girl for the kicking one, the former standing over Billy and continuing to sob. 
“All-lee! Do you want me to spank you? I will put you in the corner!” The older brother of the sisters was now turning red. “Agnes! Get! Off! My! Friend! Aran! Get away! All of you are going to bed without dinner when we get home!” 
Between groans of pain coming from both him and his dreadlocked friend AND Mike’s wrath, Billy almost didn’t notice that the girls had shut up. Even the crying angel had ceased her mewls. 
“ YU VILL NOT TALK TO SEM LIKE SAT!” 
Elizabeth had entered the fray, walking down the stairs in red plaid pajama pants and a t-shirt. With a multi-bra, Billy noticed. 
“Excuse me?” The red head boy planted his once-kicking sister on the ground. He was completely unphased by the fact he was now yelling at an anthro rabbit in pajamas. “These are my sisters, I am watching them and that means I need to lay down the law when they misbehave.” 
“ Yu do not no how to deal vis younger sisters!” 
The girls, all four of them including Aran who ran around the spiral staircase, surrounded Elizabeth, seemingly mesmerized by her presence. 
“I’d like to see you do better!”
Sitting on his knees watching the events unfold, Billy had an idea. 
“Hey! Stop!” He brushed his coat off and picked up the littlest sister, Angel. Walking to the rabbit lady, he rocked the girl in hand gently. “Why don’t you ignore what my friend said, and have a proper introduction?”
Elizabeth looked at the littlest girl, her nose twitching slightly. The little ginger smelled just like applesauce. 
“Thats Aignes, Aileen, Aran...” The boy struggled to properly hold the toddler, instead leaning towards the big bunny as if making an offer. “And this angel.”
The girl’s eyes met, Elizabeth’s pupil’s like pinpricks. Angel, looking over the furry lady like a new toy, pulled her thumb out of her mouth and said “Wabbit!”
Aran yelled, Elizabeth hopped, then Agnes and Aileen joined, and again Elizabeth was startled into jumping. Her ears twitched as the sisters raised their hands, asking for uppies, huggsies, pettsies and whatever the kid’s babbled. The rabbit seemed caught in a trap, standing absolutely still as if inside her mind was wedged between two courses of action. Before she was even able to identify what she was thinking, Billy coughed and got a little closer asked “Can you please look after them?” 
Her mouth went agape, showing off her buck teeth. “I...I...”
“Please.” Now he had put Angel right in her face, causing the rabbit’s ears to shake. “If you can watch them, we can get the job done tonight.” 
Silence. All the Callaghan sisters had their lips closed, and focus on Elizabeth. She looked at them, biting her lip. When her gaze met Angel’s, she reflexively offered to take her, to which Billy obliged.
“Vell...” Her mind raced to come up with an excuse. But, to be back in that position, going through familiar motions, like in good times of the past. All doubts ceased as she looked into the green eyes of those little girls.
“I vill do it.”
And once more the candle-lit room was filled with chaos. The little girls all bugged Elizabeth, tugging at her pajamas, poking her tail, hopping with their hands raised as if to grab her ears. And Angel laughed as Elizabeth struggled to verbally discipline them. “Stop! Down! Dont tug mein pants! No! Ach!”
Billy enjoyed the show, though he stepped back slowly to avoid any unwarranted attention. He was content, soaking in the inspiration for a mental image that he was still not necessarily okay with. But, a cute one none the less.
Mike, a weight lifted off his chest, sighed a sigh of relief and took a seat on the floor. Roger, feeling safe at last, speed walked past the horde of girls, careful not to touch any and receive their fury once more. Frank got up and pretended nothing happened, though he pointed a finger at Roger. “You’re coming?”
The short boy rubbed behind his ears. “I told my dad this was a job, and I don’t want to piss him off thinking I was lazy and got fired.”
Coming up behind Billy tapped Roger’s shoulder. “If it makes you feel any better, I have the same excuse.”
“Me too.” Said Frank. “Hey Miss Eliza, since we’re all doing this job for you does that mean we’re hired?”
The rabbit girl looked upwards as she rocked two girls in her arms. “Schiesse, does sat mean I have to pay all of you?” Her voice seemed filled with genuine worry, but she said it with a shit-eating grin. “Go dig up Dovin-Basil. Ze grave is located in ze middle of ze old cemetery.”
The boys funneled out the exit, With Billy hesitating on his way to leave. He watched as the girls, starting to come to terms that Elizabeth was not, in fact, a giant toy but another adult in their lives, began to mess with her stuff. Pulling books, shuffling chairs, climbing atop dangerously stacked furniture. “Schiessse! Stop! No! Bad!” Gripping Angel in her arms, Elizabeth glanced at him. “Everysing okay?”
“Yeah.” The boy muttered with a dumb smile across his face. 
“Come on Billy!” Yelled Roger, who had already crossed mainstreet. 
“Sen I vill see you later.”
Billy raised his hand, a slight desire to stick around and help her with the Callaghan girls. “Goodbye.”
She didn’t say goodbye back, her hand taken by Agnes as she pointed at something in the back and babbled a question. 
He watched her fade into the near-darknesss with the girl, and then he was out the door. 
